1
00:00:23,904 --> 00:00:25,548
Stop, don't look forward.

2
00:00:30,609 --> 00:00:32,413
Keep walking.

3
00:00:36,314 --> 00:00:38,273
You should address him as 'sir'
when you get in.

4
00:00:40,224 --> 00:00:41,920
Come in.

5
00:00:43,588 --> 00:00:45,032
Have a seat.

6
00:00:47,885 --> 00:00:49,749
You may feel better if you put
your hands under your legs.

7
00:00:57,064 --> 00:00:58,855
Anything you would like to confess?

8
00:00:58,890 --> 00:01:00,646
I didn't do anything.

9
00:01:02,881 --> 00:01:04,124
I don't know anything.

10
00:01:04,431 --> 00:01:06,246
You didn't do anything?
You don't know anything?

11
00:01:07,946 --> 00:01:11,767
You thought the National Security
Agency would put people
in prison at random?

12
00:01:11,865 --> 00:01:13,878
No, I didn't.

13
00:01:13,893 --> 00:01:15,207
Even if it's true that you didn't
do anything,

14
00:01:15,915 --> 00:01:18,904
we could still arrest you on the ground
of your skepticism on our government.

15
00:01:21,608 --> 00:01:25,413
Let me help you with your memory:

16
00:01:26,229 --> 00:01:31,582
Your friend and neighbor, specifically,
flied to the Federal Republic
on September 28th.

17
00:01:32,019 --> 00:01:34,398
We have evidence that it was you
who helped him with fleeing the country.

18
00:01:34,433 --> 00:01:35,960
I know nothing about it.

19
00:01:36,625 --> 00:01:40,384
He didn't tell me his plan.
I thought he was flying for business.

20
00:01:41,247 --> 00:01:45,286
Please detail what you have done
on September 28th then.

21
00:01:45,930 --> 00:01:48,945
- They've written it down.
- I want to hear it again.

22
00:01:50,445 --> 00:01:54,091
I took the kids to the park
for a walk,

23
00:01:54,214 --> 00:01:56,268
and ran into Markechner, my classmate
in high school,

24
00:01:56,915 --> 00:02:00,598
and we went to his place together,
listening to music, talking,
until it was very late.

25
00:02:01,417 --> 00:02:04,140
You can call him and confirm it.

26
00:02:04,747 --> 00:02:06,713
I can give you his number.

27
00:02:07,324 --> 00:02:10,129
From this clip it's easy for
you to find

28
00:02:10,652 --> 00:02:12,059
that he is trying to confront
his own country with his arrogance.

29
00:02:12,094 --> 00:02:15,295
It takes patience to play with him.
The next part is the interrogation,
which lasts about 40 hours.

30
00:02:16,285 --> 00:02:17,858
Let's move on.

31
00:02:23,657 --> 00:02:26,048
I want to sleep.
Let me sleep, please.

32
00:02:26,916 --> 00:02:28,431
Sleep? You need to trade for it
with something.

33
00:02:30,643 --> 00:02:34,392
Please explain again what you did
on September 28th.

34
00:02:35,940 --> 00:02:41,266
Please, let me sleep
for just one hour

35
00:02:41,589 --> 00:02:44,268
Please state again what you did
on that day.

36
00:02:50,341 --> 00:02:52,281
Why does the interrogation have
to be so long?

37
00:02:52,623 --> 00:02:54,948
I think this is inhumane.

38
00:03:01,085 --> 00:03:06,952
An innocent man, having been
questioned so long for something
he didn't do,

39
00:03:06,987 --> 00:03:09,614
he should either be in a rage
or suicidal,

40
00:03:10,382 --> 00:03:15,832
while a guilty person often refuse
to talk, or start to cry,

41
00:03:16,401 --> 00:03:18,092
because he knows exactly why
he is sitting there.

42
00:03:18,692 --> 00:03:23,960
The best way to tell whether
someone is guilty, is to question
him until he admits everything.

43
00:03:25,120 --> 00:03:27,140
We met Markechner in the park,

44
00:03:28,165 --> 00:03:30,461
then we went to his place together,

45
00:03:33,453 --> 00:03:35,679
listened to the music and
stayed up late.

46
00:03:37,473 --> 00:03:42,357
I have his telephone number,
you can give him a call and he'll
tell you what I said was true.

47
00:03:43,693 --> 00:03:46,878
Is there anything interesting
to you in his answer?

48
00:03:48,401 --> 00:03:49,760
It's the same as what he said
at the first time.

49
00:03:50,616 --> 00:03:53,546
He hardly changed a word.

50
00:03:54,375 --> 00:03:56,754
Because what really happened
would not change no matter how
you describe it.

51
00:03:57,312 --> 00:03:58,895
But there is also the possibility
that he was lying.

52
00:03:59,258 --> 00:04:04,370
Because he might have practiced it
in his mind for a thousand times.
But under coercion, he won't hold for long.

53
00:04:05,597 --> 00:04:11,780
There are other techniques
for hard rocks like him.

54
00:04:13,559 --> 00:04:17,644
If you can tell us the name
of the plane, you can go home to your
wife tonight,

55
00:04:20,034 --> 00:04:22,307
if not, it's the prison that's
waiting for you.

56
00:04:23,210 --> 00:04:24,231
Is that what you want?

57
00:04:30,410 --> 00:04:32,843
What's the name of the plane?
Who owns it?

58
00:04:34,798 --> 00:04:36,440
- Resker.
- Say it again, louder.

59
00:04:38,512 --> 00:04:41,620
Risker.
It's Bernag Resker's plane.

60
00:04:42,230 --> 00:04:44,652
Bernag Resker.

61
00:04:47,478 --> 00:04:49,622
Silence!

62
00:04:50,874 --> 00:04:51,976
Silence!

63
00:04:52,438 --> 00:04:53,653
Listen.

64
00:04:58,820 --> 00:05:00,547
Who knows what this sound is?

65
00:05:06,799 --> 00:05:09,638
This is for the trained dogs,
a piece of cloth with the criminal's
odor on it.

66
00:05:09,673 --> 00:05:14,319
It comes from every interrogation,
and will be kept in a bottle forever.

67
00:05:19,443 --> 00:05:22,306
Wiretapping is a common technique
used in almost every socialist country

68
00:05:23,552 --> 00:05:25,856
Please never forget it.
Have a nice day.

69
00:05:31,736 --> 00:05:33,288
Good! It was really good.

70
00:05:36,457 --> 00:05:38,055
Bro,

71
00:05:38,441 --> 00:05:41,005
we haven't hanged out for what,
20 years?

72
00:05:44,433 --> 00:05:47,165
And now you are a professor.

73
00:05:49,163 --> 00:05:53,618
Good for you. And I'm doing good
too, of course.

74
00:05:54,172 --> 00:05:55,958
What do you need?

75
00:05:56,633 --> 00:05:59,101
You think I want something from you?

76
00:05:59,136 --> 00:06:01,569
- I'm inviting you to a play.
- A play?

77
00:06:02,332 --> 00:06:05,189
I heard that the minister of arts
will come too.

78
00:06:06,162 --> 00:06:09,152
To show the administration's
attitude to the artists, I think.

79
00:06:09,179 --> 00:06:11,170
It starts at 7 tonight.
We'll talk about it.

80
00:06:12,179 --> 00:06:18,412
The Lives of Others

81
00:06:25,803 --> 00:06:28,282
Minister Bruno Hempf is in the middle
of the third row.

82
00:06:29,583 --> 00:06:33,397
He used to be a nobody in the
Ministry of Arts.

83
00:06:33,791 --> 00:06:36,434
And he is not particularly interested
in attending all these events.

84
00:06:43,910 --> 00:06:46,321
Georg Dreyman, he is a poet.

85
00:06:46,848 --> 00:06:51,052
He is as arrogant as
some of my students.

86
00:06:51,325 --> 00:06:52,770
Not only arrogant, but also one
of the right-wing.

87
00:06:53,692 --> 00:06:55,551
But he will lose his job soon.

88
00:06:56,042 --> 00:07:01,447
We suspect that a few writers have
been close to the Western Germany,
and he is one of them.

89
00:07:01,619 --> 00:07:03,558
The German Democratic Republic
is the best country in the world.

90
00:07:07,335 --> 00:07:09,524
It starts.

91
00:07:21,537 --> 00:07:24,536
What's wrong, my dear child?

92
00:07:24,571 --> 00:07:27,496
Marta, what happened? Tell me!

93
00:07:29,719 --> 00:07:30,973
He left me, Otto.

94
00:07:31,488 --> 00:07:34,347
Otto? How can you say that your
husband is dead?

95
00:07:34,382 --> 00:07:37,207
No, sisters, please trust me.

96
00:07:39,049 --> 00:07:41,756
He's dead already.

97
00:07:44,440 --> 00:07:47,512
There is deep fear in his paintings.

98
00:07:48,634 --> 00:07:50,537
I can see it,

99
00:07:52,012 --> 00:07:54,005
that terrifying love.

100
00:07:57,352 --> 00:07:59,876
Why does this love feel so thorny?

101
00:08:03,188 --> 00:08:06,444
Elena, let's go.

102
00:08:46,865 --> 00:08:50,393
How do you think?
Are you interested?

103
00:08:50,428 --> 00:08:52,474
I'll watch him.

104
00:08:52,509 --> 00:08:56,657
Watch him? This is totally
different from teaching.

105
00:08:56,692 --> 00:09:01,952
- We can use the best wiretappers.
- You have to risk your career.

106
00:09:01,987 --> 00:09:04,426
If you lose, you are shark meat.

107
00:09:04,461 --> 00:09:06,236
I'll be downstairs for a second.

108
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:39,419
We have a lot to do at this moment,
including a series of bans
on the culture.

109
00:09:40,415 --> 00:09:42,746
Which party do you belong to?

110
00:09:42,781 --> 00:09:45,077
I think it doesn't matter,
Mr. minister.

111
00:09:45,112 --> 00:09:47,719
What matters is one's patriotism.

112
00:09:52,262 --> 00:09:54,275
How much do you know about this man?

113
00:09:56,696 --> 00:09:57,894
Goerg Dreyman

114
00:10:02,497 --> 00:10:04,613
Maybe...

115
00:10:05,058 --> 00:10:06,083
Maybe what?

116
00:10:09,298 --> 00:10:13,535
Maybe this job is not as noble
as it seems.

117
00:10:15,800 --> 00:10:18,973
It's such a pity that you are not
a secret agent.

118
00:10:19,008 --> 00:10:26,603
I hope you could make a perfect
plan for this one. We can talk
about it later.

119
00:10:27,549 --> 00:10:29,543
They have plenty of expectations
on you.

120
00:10:32,810 --> 00:10:36,955
But this artist, he hides well.
It'll be tricky.

121
00:10:41,121 --> 00:10:44,930
Next Thursday all those felons
will attend a party at Dreyman's,

122
00:10:44,965 --> 00:10:48,719
for instance, reactionist writer Houser
and a few others. You should
plan everything carefully beforehand,

123
00:10:48,754 --> 00:10:52,474
using all your old tricks,
like wiretapping.

124
00:10:52,509 --> 00:10:56,071
Just keep an eye on his apartment,
don't try to follow him,

125
00:10:56,106 --> 00:11:01,242
and don't report before you
have gathered all the evidence.

126
00:11:05,056 --> 00:11:12,803
Once caught by us, he's dead.

127
00:11:15,106 --> 00:11:17,980
Good night, Mr. minister.

128
00:11:38,311 --> 00:11:39,593
What is he staring at us?

129
00:11:43,601 --> 00:11:45,666
What does he want?

130
00:11:46,368 --> 00:11:49,022
Is he one of your fans?

131
00:12:02,781 --> 00:12:08,809
Excuse me.
Sorry for the interruption,

132
00:12:09,411 --> 00:12:12,862
but I would like to say that it
was a fantastic night for the
art society.

133
00:12:13,557 --> 00:12:17,272
There is a famous quote:
"A poet is an engineer in the Eden."

134
00:12:17,317 --> 00:12:20,998
And Goerg Dreyman is one of our best
engineers in Democratic Republic.

135
00:12:24,383 --> 00:12:27,193
- What does he want?
- Be quiet and listen, Houser.

136
00:12:29,822 --> 00:12:36,288
I can't help giving him my compliment
again: Dreyman is a shining star among
the artists in Democratic Republic.

137
00:12:37,610 --> 00:12:42,758
Next I wish Mrs. Dreyman's beauty
and acting skills will both grow.

138
00:12:47,592 --> 00:12:51,190
- Now I see what all this is about.
- Stay with me, please.

139
00:12:53,879 --> 00:12:57,138
Please continue with the music.

140
00:12:57,516 --> 00:12:59,349
May I?

141
00:13:03,955 --> 00:13:07,415
- I love your plays.
- Thank you very much.

142
00:13:08,289 --> 00:13:10,792
And I'm very interested in you.

143
00:13:10,827 --> 00:13:11,923
Yes, I mean it.

144
00:13:12,213 --> 00:13:15,719
Engineer in the Eden?
Do you really understand what it means?

145
00:13:15,754 --> 00:13:17,907
Of course I do.

146
00:13:18,014 --> 00:13:21,164
I did throw a tons of bans
on cultural activities,

147
00:13:21,199 --> 00:13:24,925
but Houser, I'm still crazy about arts.

148
00:13:26,133 --> 00:13:32,558
The government will protect its artists,
but in the meantime, dear Dreyman,
they have to repay their government.

149
00:13:33,131 --> 00:13:35,899
I'll dance with someone else
if politics is your only topic.

150
00:13:35,934 --> 00:13:38,667
- I'm ready.
- Too late, it's too late.

151
00:13:43,746 --> 00:13:48,980
- I have been following your plays.
- Yes, following is what you do, isn't it?

152
00:13:49,015 --> 00:13:52,740
- Houser!
- That was a long time ago.

153
00:13:52,775 --> 00:13:53,934
Schweiber.

154
00:13:54,936 --> 00:13:57,081
You are busy these days, aren't you?

155
00:13:57,116 --> 00:14:01,054
Your directing is not as good
as in the past.

156
00:14:01,089 --> 00:14:02,896
Let's talk about it some other time.

157
00:14:02,931 --> 00:14:06,078
Please allow me to disagree.

158
00:14:08,520 --> 00:14:11,012
You don't have to like my plays,

159
00:14:12,388 --> 00:14:15,660
but I do love this country.

160
00:14:16,981 --> 00:14:22,100
Could you please leave politics
aside when you watch them?

161
00:14:22,135 --> 00:14:26,052
It's impossible for everyone
to share the same faith,

162
00:14:29,096 --> 00:14:34,232
but if one is truly loyal to his
faith in socialism,

163
00:14:34,864 --> 00:14:37,992
he won't change his mind no matter
what kind of plays he watches.

164
00:14:39,207 --> 00:14:41,900
- This is not something that can be banned.
- Would you like to have a try then?

165
00:14:42,960 --> 00:14:48,118
I can certainly help you get an idea of
what a ban is like if you don't believe it.

166
00:14:53,584 --> 00:14:56,188
Okay, let me put it this way:

167
00:14:56,223 --> 00:15:00,177
If my work is good to the point
of making you nervous,

168
00:15:00,212 --> 00:15:02,987
then it worths it, even if it's banned.

169
00:15:03,706 --> 00:15:07,009
- I think you should consider my advice.
- I don't need it.

170
00:15:07,336 --> 00:15:11,739
Just as you said,
I believe that a good man's love and faith

171
00:15:12,315 --> 00:15:15,631
won't be changed by one play.

172
00:15:16,055 --> 00:15:22,797
Dreyman, you can write whatever
you want, and people's mind won't
be changed so easily.

173
00:15:25,259 --> 00:15:29,774
- Have you decided on what to do?
- People listen to their conscience,

174
00:15:31,272 --> 00:15:33,283
not the nature of their jobs.

175
00:15:39,696 --> 00:15:45,110
- People should never lose hope.
- Of course, you can only become
well off when you have hope.

176
00:15:45,518 --> 00:15:49,217
Sometimes hope can be
the only thing that keeps people alive.

177
00:16:03,662 --> 00:16:06,603
Tomorrow we'll make sure everything
works fine technically.

178
00:16:07,526 --> 00:16:11,029
Most importantly,
there can't be any dead zone for
our device in his house.

179
00:16:11,585 --> 00:16:13,044
It is here?

180
00:16:16,293 --> 00:16:18,918
Good night.

181
00:17:48,879 --> 00:17:53,979
You guys are good, pals.

182
00:19:44,134 --> 00:19:45,743
20 minutes.

183
00:21:38,945 --> 00:21:44,678
Mrs. Meineke, if you tell anyone,
you won't see your family again
for the rest of your life.

184
00:21:48,009 --> 00:21:50,803
Understood?

185
00:21:51,203 --> 00:21:52,412
yes.

186
00:21:55,252 --> 00:21:58,455
Make a note on Mrs. Meineke's records.

187
00:22:10,325 --> 00:22:12,641
Happy Thursday.

188
00:22:13,419 --> 00:22:17,672
How time flies!
It's great to see you again.

189
00:22:34,949 --> 00:22:37,314
- How are you doing?
- Not too bad.

190
00:22:38,773 --> 00:22:43,054
- They don't make noise
like this all the time.
- I know, only on Thursdays.

191
00:22:44,447 --> 00:22:45,605
Yeah.

192
00:22:49,383 --> 00:22:53,685
- I miss the past.
- This doesn't sound like a good
beginning.

193
00:22:55,923 --> 00:23:00,254
- I've had this uneasy feeling since
last night's premiere.
- Good for you. It keeps you energetic.

194
00:23:08,558 --> 00:23:13,960
I can't stand this country any more.
There are no human rights, nor
freedom of speech.

195
00:23:17,134 --> 00:23:20,391
This whole system drives me mad.

196
00:23:21,289 --> 00:23:25,454
But on the other hands, it's
the same system that inspires us
to write,

197
00:23:25,892 --> 00:23:29,209
to write about how people live
in this country, real lives.

198
00:23:31,235 --> 00:23:34,516
And that's real masterpiece,
coming from our conscience.

199
00:23:39,053 --> 00:23:40,219
But I really hate it like this,
Dreyman.

200
00:23:41,437 --> 00:23:48,847
I hope I could be a writer again
in my next life.

201
00:23:52,931 --> 00:23:55,022
What would you do about this play
if you are the director?

202
00:23:57,057 --> 00:24:02,431
There are so many constraints,
you can't dig in as much as you want.

203
00:24:06,890 --> 00:24:09,237
Being alive is so meaningless.

204
00:24:11,948 --> 00:24:16,591
Albert, I think I'm in trouble.
It's the minister in charge of the arts,
minister Hempf.

205
00:24:18,252 --> 00:24:22,911
He threatened to ban my plays.

206
00:24:25,490 --> 00:24:30,009
Would it be terrible?

207
00:24:30,044 --> 00:24:32,778
I don't know what a ban is like.

208
00:24:34,920 --> 00:24:38,880
Really?

209
00:24:39,566 --> 00:24:41,266
It's great.

210
00:25:23,023 --> 00:25:28,046
The guests will come soon.
We can have a drink after they leave.

211
00:25:31,547 --> 00:25:33,719
But there are still a lot of
problems.

212
00:25:39,583 --> 00:25:42,613
Georg, you have to be strong.
I need you,

213
00:25:43,659 --> 00:25:46,785
- no matter what's gonna happen
to you in the future.
- You are my partner for my whole life.

214
00:25:46,820 --> 00:25:51,147
- You are mine too.
- Then we still have 50 years.

215
00:25:51,779 --> 00:25:53,760
Or maybe 40, right?

216
00:25:54,493 --> 00:25:58,078
I hope you didn't forget it. You
promised to tie up a Montblanc
by yourself on your birthday.

217
00:25:58,840 --> 00:26:00,195
I did, but I don't have one.

218
00:26:05,113 --> 00:26:06,257
No more excuse.

219
00:26:09,862 --> 00:26:12,572
- Are you kidding?
- You said you didn't want books
as presents anymore.

220
00:26:15,840 --> 00:26:18,517
But I doubt you can do it yourself.

221
00:26:19,094 --> 00:26:22,747
Of course I can. I know how to
do it from the day I was born.

222
00:26:24,434 --> 00:26:28,127
Don't forget I'm gonna liberate
our people on my own.

223
00:26:29,068 --> 00:26:32,210
Then you have to fasten this one
on your own first.

224
00:26:41,954 --> 00:26:45,170
Those women! I really can't do this.

225
00:27:00,469 --> 00:27:04,278
Mrs. Meineke, can you
come here for a second?

226
00:27:11,514 --> 00:27:14,582
Could you please tie my neck
tie for me?

227
00:27:19,103 --> 00:27:21,287
I'll thank you for the rest of my life.

228
00:27:26,477 --> 00:27:30,906
- Are you all right?
- Yes, I'm fine.

229
00:27:32,029 --> 00:27:33,398
Done?

230
00:27:37,389 --> 00:27:41,448
Wonderful! It's perfect.
I'll just make it look more natural.

231
00:27:42,278 --> 00:27:46,168
May I ask you to keep secret on this?
It's a secret between us.

232
00:27:58,209 --> 00:28:01,439
Nice! I really thought you wouldn't
be able to do it.

233
00:28:02,194 --> 00:28:04,396
When did you learn that?

234
00:28:04,949 --> 00:28:07,014
I learned everything when I was young.

235
00:28:12,311 --> 00:28:13,797
Our first guest is here.

236
00:28:18,879 --> 00:28:21,651
Our sweet little doorbell is broken again.
Get the door, will you?

237
00:28:21,686 --> 00:28:23,120
Okay, I will.

238
00:28:49,810 --> 00:28:52,577
- This is Our present.
- Following your instruction,

239
00:28:52,612 --> 00:28:55,345
- "No books any more".
- Thank you.

240
00:28:57,825 --> 00:29:00,733
- Can I join you guys?
- Sure. Long time no see.

241
00:29:01,280 --> 00:29:02,317
I'll get some drinks.

242
00:29:12,961 --> 00:29:15,403
What's going on?
Why is he sitting there alone?

243
00:29:15,761 --> 00:29:18,277
He hardly talked to anyone.
He just sat there and read.

244
00:29:32,229 --> 00:29:34,433
This is my present.

245
00:29:38,048 --> 00:29:42,425
- Did you just come here to read?
- It's the Brecht.

246
00:29:50,414 --> 00:29:55,510
These people don't have the thrist
for freedom, do they?

247
00:29:56,240 --> 00:29:59,742
They don't? Then why are you here?
What can we do in this environment?

248
00:30:01,428 --> 00:30:05,583
People get used to everything
around us.

249
00:30:05,618 --> 00:30:08,437
Yes, they can now accept what used
to be unbearable.

250
00:30:10,477 --> 00:30:13,682
Changes are no longer anticipated.

251
00:30:17,379 --> 00:30:21,353
You are my favorite director.
Hang on, we should talk.

252
00:30:21,388 --> 00:30:25,328
Let me explain to you the background
for the characters in this play.

253
00:30:26,516 --> 00:30:28,125
Despair, yes, exactly.

254
00:30:28,146 --> 00:30:31,968
But what should they do?

255
00:30:33,445 --> 00:30:35,978
The National Security can't
gag everybody.

256
00:30:36,013 --> 00:30:38,365
- I don't think they can.
- What the hell are you talking about?

257
00:30:38,400 --> 00:30:40,189
Houser!
What's up?

258
00:30:40,903 --> 00:30:43,535
Schweiber, I'm really sorry.
My friend is a little drunk.

259
00:30:46,585 --> 00:30:49,457
What's with you? Don't you know
that he's working for the National
Security now?

260
00:30:49,492 --> 00:30:52,067
No, Houser.
You don't know him well.

261
00:31:10,827 --> 00:31:13,833
You are being idealistic,
you know that?

262
00:31:13,868 --> 00:31:15,783
Since when have you been escaping
the reality?

263
00:31:15,818 --> 00:31:18,796
They transformed you, all these
people. You are now used to your
life under despotism.

264
00:31:19,480 --> 00:31:22,373
If that's true, you don't even
deserve to be alive.

265
00:31:22,979 --> 00:31:28,119
Don't see me again until you want
to end all this.

266
00:31:56,727 --> 00:32:00,996
- Some people still gave you books.
- Was my request too impolite?

267
00:32:01,549 --> 00:32:05,239
Look at this fork.
Isn't it beautiful?

268
00:32:05,861 --> 00:32:07,558
That's for making salad.

269
00:32:08,677 --> 00:32:11,065
No matter what it's for,
it's beautiful.

270
00:32:13,035 --> 00:32:16,391
Look at this.
I'll write with this pen.

271
00:32:17,468 --> 00:32:19,470
It's from Thomas. I wouldn't
count on his taste for presents.

272
00:32:20,979 --> 00:32:23,255
Some of these are pretty useful.

273
00:32:37,294 --> 00:32:41,085
- This is from Albert.
- Then you are going to love it.

274
00:32:45,294 --> 00:32:48,085
"Sonata from Good Men"

275
00:33:10,294 --> 00:33:19,085
"11:04pm: 'Lazlo' and CMS unpacked
the presents. We speculated that
they had sex afterwards"

276
00:33:21,995 --> 00:33:23,647
You are late!

277
00:33:24,537 --> 00:33:29,485
I'm sorry. Something happened
just before I left home.

278
00:33:29,520 --> 00:33:31,157
So I'm late for four minutes.
I apologize.

279
00:33:39,841 --> 00:33:43,942
They've started doing that?
These artists! What can't they do?

280
00:33:44,840 --> 00:33:50,946
I have to listen to this, how
their sex lives are different
from ordinary people.

281
00:33:54,402 --> 00:33:55,969
See you tomorrow at 11am.

282
00:34:03,673 --> 00:34:09,024
Albert Jerska, an old customer.
He's been banned to the core.

283
00:34:09,059 --> 00:34:11,034
I knew they were close.
come on, let's go lunch.

284
00:34:21,225 --> 00:34:26,209
"Volleyball game
at 7pm tonight."

285
00:34:26,244 --> 00:34:28,369
I suggest we sit there.

286
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:31,239
No matter where we sit,
socialism must let us eat.

287
00:34:37,704 --> 00:34:43,058
There is one thing I want you
to know, that is

288
00:34:45,036 --> 00:34:47,937
it was the Minister's car that
sent Mrs. Dreyman home last night.

289
00:34:50,647 --> 00:34:54,313
We don't know the details yet,

290
00:34:54,348 --> 00:35:02,080
but he didn't deny it when I
talked to him last time.

291
00:35:03,407 --> 00:35:08,041
Once you find anything between
the minister and Mrs. Dreyman,
just tell me, don't write it down.

292
00:35:09,822 --> 00:35:14,893
What you are listening to not only
determines my future, but yours too,

293
00:35:16,585 --> 00:35:17,610
if we do find something.

294
00:35:23,757 --> 00:35:28,335
Why should we cover up for him?
This is not our style.

295
00:35:28,370 --> 00:35:32,918
Personal affairs can be powerful
weapons for our rival parties.

296
00:35:34,065 --> 00:35:37,081
He and us are all communists,
You don't want disgrace your
own party, do you?

297
00:35:37,877 --> 00:35:43,399
I have a new joke, it's like this:
Erich (General Secretary) went into
his office in the morning.

298
00:35:43,434 --> 00:35:48,629
He opened the window, saw the sun,
and said...what's wrong?

299
00:35:53,070 --> 00:35:56,280
Sorry, I'm just...I...

300
00:35:56,315 --> 00:36:02,365
It's all right, comrade.
It's okay to tell jokes about
leaders of our country.

301
00:36:03,642 --> 00:36:05,230
I can tell a ton of them myself.

302
00:36:08,412 --> 00:36:09,514
Go on, please.

303
00:36:11,402 --> 00:36:16,471
Okay. Erich, our general secretary,

304
00:36:17,633 --> 00:36:19,917
he said to the sun: "Good morning,
my dear sun."

305
00:36:20,000 --> 00:36:24,033
"Good morning, my dear sun."
Is that what he said?

306
00:36:26,000 --> 00:36:30,033
And the sun answered:
"Good morning."

307
00:36:30,999 --> 00:36:35,302
At noon he asked again:"Good day,
my dear sun?"

308
00:36:35,666 --> 00:36:39,656
And the sun said:"Good day."
After work in the evening, Erich
greeted again:

309
00:36:39,691 --> 00:36:43,646
"Good evening, my dear sun."
But the sun didn't answer this time.

310
00:36:44,678 --> 00:36:48,626
So he asked once again:"Good evening,
dear sun, what's up?"

311
00:36:48,661 --> 00:36:51,586
The sun said:"You bastard, don't
'What's up' me, I've been tolerant
for a whole day!"

312
00:36:57,568 --> 00:36:59,875
Your name?

313
00:37:00,358 --> 00:37:01,787
ID number? Department?

314
00:37:02,982 --> 00:37:04,086
Me?

315
00:37:07,009 --> 00:37:09,136
My name is Stiller.

316
00:37:09,288 --> 00:37:12,095
Adolph Stiller. I'm in the
First Informational Section.

317
00:37:12,130 --> 00:37:16,174
You don't have to hear from me
how much damage you just did to
your own career, do you?

318
00:37:19,224 --> 00:37:24,810
- Well...I just...
- You just what?

319
00:37:24,845 --> 00:37:27,512
This kind of jokes will blemish
our party.

320
00:37:27,547 --> 00:37:30,041
And you are working in the National
Security Agency.

321
00:37:30,076 --> 00:37:33,383
Why don't you just go to his office
and tell the minister that joke?

322
00:37:44,758 --> 00:37:50,700
Yeah, it kills me!
Good story, but needs work.

323
00:37:50,735 --> 00:37:54,001
What's the difference between
Erich and a telephone?

324
00:37:54,036 --> 00:37:58,596
Not at all. You just grab and
dial for both.

325
00:38:37,049 --> 00:38:43,049
- Where are you going?
- Home.
- Night.

326
00:38:51,296 --> 00:38:52,506
Get in the car!

327
00:38:55,240 --> 00:38:58,688
You didn't forget about our date
on every Thursday, did you?

328
00:38:59,240 --> 00:39:02,688
Is your poet having his birthday again?

329
00:39:05,571 --> 00:39:08,751
Get in the car! come on!

330
00:39:20,740 --> 00:39:22,226
I believe you understand
what's good for you.

331
00:39:37,000 --> 00:39:41,730
So please think about it and
weigh the options in your mind.

332
00:39:56,325 --> 00:39:59,830
Maybe it is your coldness

333
00:39:59,831 --> 00:40:02,506
that makes me so crazy about you.

334
00:40:12,352 --> 00:40:14,256
Are you out of your mind?

335
00:40:16,809 --> 00:40:19,332
If you want to get home early,

336
00:40:20,382 --> 00:40:26,554
don't fight. I'll send you
home early if you behave yourself.

337
00:41:18,449 --> 00:41:20,225
You'd better see it with your
own eyes.

338
00:41:36,629 --> 00:41:38,789
I'm coming!

339
00:41:47,115 --> 00:41:48,429
Silly woman!

340
00:42:10,086 --> 00:42:15,287
See you next Thursday.
Let's go.

341
00:44:29,598 --> 00:44:31,324
Are you asleep?

342
00:44:33,100 --> 00:44:34,888
Hold me, please.

343
00:45:04,366 --> 00:45:06,019
How are you, sir?

344
00:45:07,916 --> 00:45:10,062
You are five minutes late again.

345
00:45:51,335 --> 00:45:55,322
Good evening. Eleventh Floor,
the door on the right.

346
00:45:55,357 --> 00:45:57,895
Open the door.

347
00:46:02,344 --> 00:46:06,594
- How did you get up here?
- I know your name.

348
00:46:09,024 --> 00:46:10,792
I was able to get in just by
telling your name, can you
believe it?

349
00:46:11,755 --> 00:46:12,896
No, I can't.

350
00:46:26,348 --> 00:46:30,382
How was it? Did you like it?

351
00:46:36,914 --> 00:46:39,936
- Stay for the night.
- I can't.

352
00:46:39,971 --> 00:46:42,650
I have another customer.

353
00:46:44,218 --> 00:46:46,220
I work on reservations.

354
00:46:52,473 --> 00:46:55,903
It's 1:30 already, what kind of
customer is that at this time?

355
00:46:55,938 --> 00:46:59,067
None of your business.

356
00:47:01,257 --> 00:47:03,640
You can reserve for an hour longer
next time.

357
00:47:03,675 --> 00:47:04,772
See ya.

358
00:48:08,598 --> 00:48:12,223
Georg, have you heard about Houser?

359
00:48:13,197 --> 00:48:14,486
No, what's about him?

360
00:48:14,521 --> 00:48:17,523
National Security took
his passport, he can't go
abroad to attend the workshop.

361
00:48:20,279 --> 00:48:22,035
It's because he's too proud, you know?
The Security finally had to do something.

362
00:48:22,070 --> 00:48:25,075
A man who doesn't know how to
protect himself. He deserves it.

363
00:48:26,965 --> 00:48:29,549
A writer should be more conscious
about the reality.

364
00:48:33,965 --> 00:48:42,549
"'Lazlo' supported the forbidance
on Houser's travel abroad."

365
00:48:50,787 --> 00:48:53,425
Have you seen my anthology?

366
00:48:53,460 --> 00:48:54,493
The one I just finished writing.

367
00:48:56,115 --> 00:48:57,761
Isn't it on your desk?

368
00:48:59,235 --> 00:49:01,635
This is weird. I can't find it.

369
00:49:01,670 --> 00:49:07,250
* Brecht *
"Everyday in September the early fall
was blue;

370
00:49:08,240 --> 00:49:13,480
"Those young upright trees reaching
for the sky, like love they flourished
and grew;

371
00:49:14,743 --> 00:49:20,004
"Above us floated the fair clear sky;

372
00:49:20,039 --> 00:49:22,871
"which a cotton-white cloud
was walking through;

373
00:49:22,906 --> 00:49:26,897
"And with faith in your heart
it shall never leave you."

374
00:49:46,840 --> 00:49:48,876
- Yes?
- Georg? This is Vagner.

375
00:49:48,911 --> 00:49:50,589
What's up?

376
00:49:52,315 --> 00:49:57,694
Have you heard?
Jerska killed himself.

377
00:50:04,754 --> 00:50:06,403
Georg?

378
00:50:08,252 --> 00:50:10,373
I'm sad too.

379
00:51:53,707 --> 00:51:57,647
I've been thinking about the last
conversation between Jerska and me.

380
00:52:00,534 --> 00:52:03,679
I should listen to him and
make some change.

381
00:52:08,877 --> 00:52:14,096
If he could hear this song I'm playing,

382
00:52:14,131 --> 00:52:17,740
if he really can,
he would know what I'm gonna do.

383
00:52:49,541 --> 00:52:52,131
Do you really Work for the National
Security Agency?

384
00:52:56,679 --> 00:52:59,659
Do you know what National Security
Agency is for?

385
00:53:00,293 --> 00:53:05,494
Yes. They are bad guys, they took
my dad.

386
00:53:06,370 --> 00:53:07,560
Did they?

387
00:53:07,983 --> 00:53:09,881
What's the name of your...?

388
00:53:13,233 --> 00:53:14,905
My what?

389
00:53:16,620 --> 00:53:18,336
Your ball.
What's the name of your ball?

390
00:53:19,103 --> 00:53:22,486
You are strange.
Why would people name their balls?

391
00:53:28,443 --> 00:53:32,565
Minister, this is my present
for you,

392
00:53:32,600 --> 00:53:35,636
The best wiretappers,
and the top operators.

393
00:53:36,986 --> 00:53:38,841
- We can hear every sound in every corner.
- You must find what we need from Dreyman.

394
00:53:40,757 --> 00:53:44,169
Jerska killed himself, and these
artists will do something.

395
00:53:48,402 --> 00:53:49,633
It was good to see you.

396
00:53:57,794 --> 00:54:03,239
You should work on this, we're gonna
start watching Houser and others.

397
00:54:05,677 --> 00:54:09,871
The Minister really wants to
go for it now.

398
00:54:09,906 --> 00:54:13,451
It's giving me headaches.

399
00:54:13,486 --> 00:54:21,477
- What's new with him and Mrs. Dreyman?
- If I didn't hear it wrong, they are
going out tomorrow night.

400
00:54:21,512 --> 00:54:25,589
Good, good.
But don't spend too much time on
this love story.

401
00:54:26,988 --> 00:54:28,402
We have our own business to mind.

402
00:54:29,098 --> 00:54:31,514
Don't forget that.

403
00:54:42,719 --> 00:54:45,696
I've been queasy tonight.

404
00:54:46,212 --> 00:54:48,960
I don't want to stay home by myself,
and I can't write anything.

405
00:54:50,662 --> 00:54:55,048
After Jerska's death,
I don't feel like writing anymore.

406
00:54:57,236 --> 00:54:59,030
And I start to fear that you
would leave me.

407
00:55:00,910 --> 00:55:02,795
Don't be like a child.

408
00:55:05,001 --> 00:55:07,528
- I have to go out tonight anyway.
- Where?

409
00:55:09,066 --> 00:55:11,646
An old schoolmate is coming,

410
00:55:12,309 --> 00:55:13,629
- And we are gonna...
- You are not lying to me, are you?

411
00:55:16,357 --> 00:55:19,121
- Is that true?
- What do you mean?

412
00:55:19,485 --> 00:55:24,141
I know everything.

413
00:55:26,429 --> 00:55:28,461
I know where you are going.

414
00:55:31,109 --> 00:55:32,986
And I beg you not to.

415
00:55:34,188 --> 00:55:36,440
You don't have to do this.

416
00:55:37,259 --> 00:55:39,503
You don't have to.

417
00:55:47,500 --> 00:55:49,171
I know you are doing this for me,

418
00:55:51,372 --> 00:55:53,475
and for acting, which you can
never give up.

419
00:55:55,407 --> 00:55:56,736
Trust me,

420
00:55:59,569 --> 00:56:01,603
Christa Maria,

421
00:56:02,076 --> 00:56:04,272
You are a great artist,

422
00:56:06,505 --> 00:56:10,222
you always are. I know it.

423
00:56:11,937 --> 00:56:13,575
And your audience know it too.

424
00:56:13,610 --> 00:56:17,688
There is no need for you to
please anyone.

425
00:56:17,723 --> 00:56:20,047
Don't go.

426
00:56:20,082 --> 00:56:21,820
Don't go to him.

427
00:56:25,654 --> 00:56:32,629
No, I don't need to do this.
I did everything in vain.

428
00:56:35,845 --> 00:56:38,792
But what about you?

429
00:56:38,984 --> 00:56:41,845
Don't you need it?
Do you want to give up your freedom?

430
00:56:43,529 --> 00:56:45,649
You can live in your writing,

431
00:56:45,684 --> 00:56:47,004
you can still write whatever in
your mind. Then why didn't you?

432
00:56:47,039 --> 00:56:52,699
Because you know they will destroy you.
People can't just live on faith.

433
00:56:55,497 --> 00:57:01,121
What can we do?
What should we do?

434
00:57:04,669 --> 00:57:06,489
Do you want to be the next Jerska?

435
00:57:07,557 --> 00:57:09,214
I don't.

436
00:57:10,000 --> 00:57:11,667
So I have to go now.

437
00:57:13,620 --> 00:57:17,775
You're making a point.
I can't make you change your mind.

438
00:57:21,058 --> 00:57:22,402
But I beg you,

439
00:57:22,437 --> 00:57:26,559
don't go.
Cherish yourself.

440
00:57:26,594 --> 00:57:28,428
I'm here, sir.

441
00:57:29,532 --> 00:57:32,136
What were you listening to?
You were so concentrated.

442
00:57:34,762 --> 00:57:36,103
Okay, it's my turn.

443
00:57:36,138 --> 00:57:39,015
I can't take the blame to make
you work overtime.

444
00:57:49,015 --> 00:57:52,460
Where are you going?

445
00:57:53,739 --> 00:57:56,479
To see one of my old schoolmates.

446
00:58:02,134 --> 00:58:04,222
I'll write down the details.
You shall see them tomorrow morning.

447
00:58:04,621 --> 00:58:06,313
Don't worry.

448
00:58:09,481 --> 00:58:11,797
Good night.

449
00:59:02,203 --> 00:59:04,165
There are plenty of seats inside.

450
00:59:13,880 --> 00:59:14,955
Just myself.

451
00:59:17,713 --> 00:59:20,327
Give me a cup of vodka.

452
00:59:21,060 --> 00:59:22,551
Okay.

453
00:59:29,081 --> 00:59:31,219
Can you play "The Smile" instead?

454
00:59:45,205 --> 00:59:47,359
Wine, please.

455
01:00:37,836 --> 01:00:38,938
How do you do, madam?

456
01:00:39,740 --> 01:00:42,020
Please don't bother me.
Leave me alone.

457
01:00:42,800 --> 01:00:44,653
Mrs. Sieland.

458
01:00:44,688 --> 01:00:47,577
Do we know each other?

459
01:00:47,612 --> 01:00:50,111
You don't know me,
but I know you well.

460
01:00:53,001 --> 01:00:54,826
People love you,

461
01:00:54,861 --> 01:00:56,711
because you are real.

462
01:01:01,344 --> 01:01:05,917
- Actresses can't be real.
- But you are.

463
01:01:11,182 --> 01:01:13,768
I've seen you on stage,

464
01:01:13,803 --> 01:01:19,215
and you were just yourself,

465
01:01:22,490 --> 01:01:24,147
like who you are now.

466
01:01:27,928 --> 01:01:29,290
You think you know who I am?

467
01:01:30,032 --> 01:01:31,743
I'm one of your audience.

468
01:01:37,381 --> 01:01:40,327
- I have to go.
- Where are you going?

469
01:01:42,747 --> 01:01:45,426
I'm going to see an old schoolmate
of mine.

470
01:01:45,461 --> 01:01:49,440
Really? You become a different
person when you're lying.

471
01:01:51,428 --> 01:01:53,831
- Do I?
- Yes.

472
01:02:06,046 --> 01:02:10,140
Am I still the Christa Maria you know?

473
01:02:12,899 --> 01:02:18,310
Would you leave someone who is even
more important than your own life?

474
01:02:22,525 --> 01:02:25,241
Would you give away your body for art?

475
01:02:25,783 --> 01:02:28,445
Give away your body for art?

476
